# GPU cloth: no sim readbacks

Cloth simulation state **must not cross the GPU→CPU boundary** during gameplay. The solver, connectivity, attachment, and duel metrics run on **GPU compute** only.

## Never do

- `getArrayBufferAsync` on **vertex positions**, **edge buffers**, or **full assembly** reconstruction for gameplay logic
- Per-frame CPU loops over thousands of particles, vertices, or edges copied from GPU
- `readCurrentClothAssembly()` (or equivalent) on the hot path for UI, health, or combat
- `await` health or topology work inside the frame loop in a way that stalls on large buffer readbacks
- “Fix it on CPU” shortcuts when GPU data is wrong—fix the compute shader or uniforms

## Allowed (minimal)

- **UI scalars only**: read back ≤16 bytes per frame interval (e.g. two `float` health values) for DOM/HUD—not cloth meshes or buffers
- **One-time boot/dress** tooling in tests or dev-only debug, clearly gated—not every frame in duel/character modes
- CPU use of **static topology** captured at load (edge graph, fighter masks, dress baseline counts)—not live sim positions

## Required pattern

1. **Compute** on GPU (TSL / `renderer.compute`) using existing storage buffers (`vertexPositionBuffer`, `edgeActiveBuffer`, bone SDF buffers, etc.)
2. **Reduce** on GPU (per-particle pass + single-invocation sum, or future atomics)—never sum on CPU from a full particle readback
3. **Display**: optional throttled read of a small `duelHealthResult` (or similar) buffer; default every 12+ sim frames, not every topology tick
4. **Topology / tear**: duel assembly has **no** `refreshClothTopologyFromGpu` / edge readback / CPU connectivity rebuild; render uses dress-time index buffer; `syncEdgeVisualForRender` keeps edge state on GPU; health uses GPU reduce + 16-byte UI readback only

## When adding features (health, tears, attachment)

- Ask: “Can this be a few floats out of a result buffer?”
- If yes → GPU compute + tiny readback
- If no → redesign (sample on GPU, hierarchical reduce, or shader-driven render)—do not read all particles

